The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic since this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is mature enough and our operators offer virtually all services like their partners in Western Europe.
There is still something missing – a virtual operator that obliges traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be missing for long.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most dear ones in Europe has already been written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end ČTÚ also confirmed it, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regularising roaming tariffs perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible for prices in the Czech Republic to remain so high in relation to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks the competition that would really like to start the fight .
Perhaps it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and cover highly above 100 %.
Instead, mobile telephony operators like to complain about the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, he also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his network has probably no more possibilities. (Otherwise it might be difficult to find other frequencies now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a substantial reduction in prices, to which traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time even before the entry of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices were heard in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that the place for operators of this kind exists and that they can really succeed.
At the end of the day, we must not go too far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the Virtual Operator Mobilking in Poland.
In only half a year this operator has managed to conquer more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which the Czech Republic belongs, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete brewing group.
In order to actually work, many fewer customers are enough than a traditional operator.
They do not carry behind, i.e. relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present at low cost, offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
So for example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that cost at least half of its competitors.
But as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland can be a pretty good move even the bet on a group-blow not very soon.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"The real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also affirm a concept similar to that of Poland.
He doubts the press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of the services it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We talk about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have many expectations.
Mobilking's ignition will take place rather in the other countries of our area," said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It has thus confirmed indirectly that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very favourable to this thought.
Instead, try to do everything because you don't create any potential competitors.
For some time now, he has not been hiding his interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefonika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And it's better first.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them," says the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl group.
So maybe better times will come.
From unofficial information it emerges that the first virtual operator may have to have it by the end of the year.
But for now around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for creating a virtual operator in full title.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has turned to us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the press section of Telefonika O2.
The specific features of the Czech market also apply to other operators.
The press spokesman for T-Mobil Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 declaration: "For now we have not noticed any vital and advantageous commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
And he adds: "On the T-Mobile network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point we will have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone concentrates his attention rather than reaching his demands for the 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the context of the sharing of expenditure and infrastructure.
Let us consider this, from the point of view of the customers, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
The competent authorities - with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile telephony operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thereby reduce profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The discomforts around the creation U:fon testify that when operators hold to something they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure imposed on ČTÚ during the creation period of U:phone to the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public access information from ČTÚ websites.
But right now U:fon serves as a topic for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: "The environment of competition in the mobile telephony market has been little further enhanced with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would focus on him and above all on his high claims services."
However, the attitude of mobile operators is quite surprising the complete lack of interest by Czech regulators.
It is not only the attitude of ČTÚ that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in the economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, this with regard to the whole problem has taken its typical position.
"The virtual operator's entry into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract of rental of the necessary infrastructure between mobile operator and virtual operator had been realized.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, of the section for UOHS external relations, in response to our questioning.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators may not be surprising.
Instead, the office that needs to defend the interests of consumers and, above all, to deal with the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lowering prices for mobile phone services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of UOHS.
Truly shocking throughout the situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is on its own.
Equally as the same price of petrol for all petrol is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it has no corresponding greater responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The necessary instruments for the opening up of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be lacking by the telecommunications regulator," mentioned Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points .
Of course there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator the agreement of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has – at the end of the accounts logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not accept this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators do in such a strange way.
At the same time the complaints by the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly frequent makeup with which UOHS is held out of the whole matter.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to promote the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that many experts expected to improve the situation.
This fact the representatives of UOHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it when no one's watching
While we do not realize that these pseudo-virtual operators remain functioning, some of which even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile telephone services which are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the people who are set.
The magic is in the fact that the company vis-à-vis the operator appears as a classic company customer, which orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a presale.
"If the cases you are discussing, of which we will be interested, could be a breach of the contractual conditions, and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with this company," replied Martina Kemrová.
But it is unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of the persons responsible for mobile phone operators.
Especially in the case of the 3 companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator at the same time defends himself from such an attitude.
From the activities of these companies, they are profiting in no way indifferent and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - are not harmed in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the usual customers of mobile phone operators "
But this should be a little bit odd to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another question arises for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has rights strong enough to reveal similar activities and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and whose commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile telephony market has led to a substantial reduction in prices for services.
At the same time in virtually all the countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small market, too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries in these cases the regulatory bodies have intervened in defence, not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and he joined others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators launch each other the whole case like a hot potato.
For our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of competence in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But we don't throw away the sponge.
If the information of the backstage is right and the virtual operator will really appear from us soon, the Czech mobile phone market will be back in motion.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only hardly UOHS could remain impassable to the refusal (discrimination) of the other concerned.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than in the rest of Europe.
