Talking in sleep
Some children talk at night.
I refer not to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them on the previous day, but to those children who speak by staying asleep.
The first time that happens, at best you get scared, but it doesn't really matter very much.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called sleep.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely most of you have told me that you talked in your sleep.
This phenomenon may occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason why this phenomenon can be explained.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (make it pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but it is not necessarily so.
As already mentioned above can be associated with very high stages of fever, stress or distress.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that has not yet been studied.
Also the intensity with which it appears is extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that happens the opposite (scream, scream, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, you should observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there are any issues that are generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet for the situation.
We said that it is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g. if coupled with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child excessively before he goes to sleep.
Propose peaceful games and avoid television programs or series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them gain a certain inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once sleepwalkers show up trying to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
