The meeting - The blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDecary, had every reason to rejoice, since Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Transfusion Service of the Canadian Red Cross were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such a drama and population protests, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying writing a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people said they still believed in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the next few years, we gained public confidence," explains before saying proud that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population had already trusted in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, telling her that she has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't know whether that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
There is therefore one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, that when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, measures of exclusion are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been demonstrated that this disease is clearly transmitted by infected blood.
This episode has shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique appeared on the market for the identification of HIV: the tests of nucleic acid (TAN) that allow the presence of the virus in donor blood to be recognized directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, or since the person contracted the disease to what the first viruses can be identified in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them is thus greatly reduced.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500,000 blood samples annually, it will take more than 24 years before an HIV case is found with a transfusion.
I believe that today you can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the Hema-Québec leadership.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus, like the West Nile virus, appeared on the Island of Réunion, was transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continued before stressing that besides having safe resources, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"Necessities increase as the population ages.
Being the most aggressive cancer cures, patients often need a intake of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences on the number of donors who on average constitute only 3% of Quebec's population acceptable as donors."
All healthy people who have reached 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of those offering themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is disseminated, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
The cases of shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so frenetic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, of which bone transplants, heart valves eye globes and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before they are deposited at the Héma-Québec which manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abundant blood rich in stem cells that can serve to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of taking cord blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they can't access you," because Héma-Québec does not have the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
