The intelligent machine mimics the flight of the skull
What could be the best way to develop anticollition technologies if you do not imitate the sensors of the obstacles that are in nature?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project presented to CEATEC in Japan, the Calabrians gave the initial strategic direction to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collition systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo the Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotized mini-auto with the properties of the bees, with the ultimate aim of creating a system able to scan all the collisions.
Flying the bees form their own oval personal space that really resembles our protective shield - explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and research and development.
Important is the role of the view of the ape, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
Engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the ape view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, changes direction immediately turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, is carried out in a completely instinctive way.
"If it weren't so the robot car wouldn't react fast to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot auto project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the harmful and more internal layer of the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what makes a bee to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in an eyebrow.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering the wheels.
Instead of the endless possibilities available to bees to scan other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, speed up and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by batteries to lithium polymers, lighter and high energy density, which means that their duration is greater than that of lithium ions.
According to Andoh it is important the instantity of the intelligent reaction, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot must process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it uses only a memory of a few tens of Kb.
There's no need for a memory of gigabyte or megabyte.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions which, they predict to Nissan, can be installed on standard vehicles within 10 years.
Further possibilities of application can be represented by unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding obstacles on the road leads to destination.
