Today in Paris the European Summit for Equal Opportunity began, organised this year by France with the Presidency of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, MP Fidesz of the European People's Party in the message addressed to the plenary as the main rapporteur of the congress, drew attention to school segregation because it is the most serious legal violation affecting Roma children and the most serious obstacle to their affirmation.
Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, on behalf of the French Presidency, and European Commissioner Vladimir Špidla responsible for employment, social affairs and equal opportunities, opened the conference at the highest level.
Among those invited to the conference were the governments, the European social partners and representatives of the major European civil and rights organisations within equal opportunities.
Járóka, according to the press office of the Group of the Party of European Socialists, recalled, in addition to discrimination in recruitments, that the Roma are evicted from the labour market primarily because of their low schooling.
"Most Roma young people do not qualify as middle-level students and as a result of elementary education of poor quality only an ironic number of them can reach a higher degree of education."
Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in promoting human rights.
Investing in the education of Roma children can mean strengthening the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the honourable Member, it is necessary to make aware of these links in the wider area between the Roma and non-Romans.
In fact, as soon as a Roma school starts, its chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market increase; through taxes paid for income and consumption contribute to the nation's budget.
"The right of European citizenship of the Roma must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and segregated schools" - stressed Lívia Járóka.
According to the honourable Member, the union of purpose and action of the European Union is necessary to speed up the process of disintegration of schools, and that is why it is essential to respect the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"The vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be interrupted, Roma children must be given the opportunities granted by the democratic space so that they can contribute as citizens in full title to the future of Europe" - he asked Járóka.
In the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunity" to ensure for all, the aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized every year, the Berlin meeting last year is to ensure a unique forum to promote anti-discrimination objectives and equal opportunities set at the state and European level.
